nt|^b@2^z@3

|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Today some of the best pairs in the world use systems based on Precision including Meckstroth & Rodwell and many others and it has tended to edge out most of the other "Strong Club" systems that have appeared over the years.

So why has Precision succeeded when so many other Strong Club systems have fallen by the wayside? 

I feel the secret is that whilst Precision is fairly prescriptive in a few sequences, it remains at it's heart a very simple and consistent system that delivers the goods. The basic concepts behind it are easy enough to learn and they alone are enough to give you an edge against the likes of Acol, Standard American, 2/1, etc. 

Once you add on the "optional extras" and, best of all, the Asking Bids that turn Precision into "Super-Precision", you have a system that, for my money, most the others out of the water and, perhaps best of all, is ENORMOUS fun to play (just ask any of our Precision group). 

The trick is to take as much of the guesswork out of bidding as you can. Where so-called "Natural" systems often end up leaving you wondering whether partner has good enough trumps, or what their exact distribution is, or whether they have the Queen of Diamonds as well as the Ace.

Precision often leaves you able to write partner's exact hand down before you make the final bid of the auction knowing it's exactly the right contract. If you think that is an idle boast then to whet your appetite as to the sort of sequences precision can offer, take the following hand, which is taken from an actual tournament that Jason Hackett and I played in the 1980's: 
