|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Let's discuss a few general things about Precision.   Precision initially is fairly strict about point-count requirements for opening bids.

This is not to say that playing strength plays no part in deciding whether to open (or what to open) - far from it, but although Precision is a fairly aggressive system, it puts less faith in "adding" points for extra suit length than systems like Standard American or 2/1. 

Similarly, when responder is assessing their hand, it is the point-count that is initially paramount. Playing strength, trump support and ruffing values obviously play a part in assessing a hand, but the idea of adding points specifically for shortages when assessing limit bids is an alien concept to Precision. 

Indeed, limit bids in suits rather than No Trumps is not something that Precision really uses.  Direct suit raises (especially in a Major) tend to be more pre-emptive than anything else and good raises tend to follow a different route. 

Over Minor suit Openings, if Responder is interested in exploring, the general tactics are normally aimed at playing "somewhere else", for example by finding a 4-4 Major suit fit or playing in No Trumps if possible.  

That's not to say that we never play in a Minor suit game or part-score, of course.

The general features that "Classic" Precision encompasses are as follows:

^c@.^d1@C shows 16+ and all intermediate Openings show 11-15.
^c@.^d13-15 1NT Opening.
^c@.^dForcing 1NT Response to 1@H and 1@S Openings (Similar to 2/1)
^c@.^d2@C Opening shows 5+ Clubs and is intermediate
^c@.^d5-card Majors
|
