|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  If you ARE serious about learning the system, it is best done as a PARTNERSHIP whereby two of you learn the system together. This is because the system demands comprehensive partnership understandings.

This is NOT a system you can start playing with a complete stranger with any degree of confidence, even if they know the system well. Our suggestion, therefore, is that you find yourself a regular partner who is also interested in learning the system. Learn together, practice and play together, and discuss the system together.

The Partnership Bidding tables on BBO, if you've not yet discovered them, are a truly wonderful asset. Jason Hackett and I would have sold our mothers for that kind of facility when we were devising and developing the system together.

Ok, I wrote the system for the most part as it stand today, much of it with Jason Hackett, but Jason and I practiced the system for 6 MONTHS before playing it in anger Much of that time was spent in discussion, of course, but it does show that it takes a fairly serious amount of commitment to learn this stuff.

One of the BIG advantages to learning this system is that there are a considerable number of people on BBO who now play this system, so there are people whom you've not partnered before with whom you will be able to sit down and play this system without a lot of discussion.

The other facility that will really help you is Full Disclosure. We have not one but 12 different Full Disclosure cards available for download from the website with different implementations of the system. These are a great learning tool in the early stages of learning the system.

If you've not encountered FD before, it is primarily a means of alerting Opps automatically about your bids, but as you can set it to show you the meaning of bids you are THINKING of making as well as bids that you and partner have already made, it is a fantastic tool when first learning the system.

Once you've learned the system you can "turn off" that feature so that only Opps see the alerts These FDCC cards range from relatively basic implementations of the system, through cards for use against other pairs playing Precision, and even versions for the full "complex" system (not the version taught in these sessions).
